While setting up a project using 8 adc channels per ADC, i noticed that an assertion would fail at runtime whenever more than 6 channels were used. For example this task:
```
#[embassy_executor::task]
pub async fn adc_1_task(p: Peripherals) {
    let adc_data1: &mut [u16; ADC_BUF_SIZE] =
        singleton!(ADCDAT1 : [u16; ADC_BUF_SIZE] = [0u16; ADC_BUF_SIZE]).unwrap();

    let adc = Adc::new(p.ADC1);

    let mut adc: RingBufferedAdc<embassy_stm32::peripherals::ADC1> =
        adc.into_ring_buffered(p.DMA2_CH0, adc_data1);

    let mut pa0 = p.PA0;
    let mut pa1 = p.PA1;
    let mut pa2 = p.PA2;
    let mut pa3 = p.PA3;
    let mut pc0 = p.PC0;
    let mut pc1 = p.PC1;
    let mut pc2 = p.PC2;
    let mut pc3 = p.PC3;

    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::One, &mut pa0, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PA0 is 1st
    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::Two, &mut pa1, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PA1 is 2nd
    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::Three, &mut pa2, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PA2 is 3rd
    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::Four, &mut pa3, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PA3 is 4th
    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::Five, &mut pc0, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PC0 is 5th
    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::Six, &mut pc1, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PC1 is 6th
    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::Seven, &mut pc2, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PC2 is 7th
    adc.set_sample_sequence(Sequence::Eight, &mut pc3, SAMPLE_TIME_COMMON); // PC3 is 8th

    let mut buffer1 = [0u16; ADC_BUF_SIZE / 2];
    loop {
        match adc.read(&mut buffer1).await {
            Ok(_data) => {
                info!("\n adc1: {} n = {}", buffer1[0..16], _data);
            }
            Err(e) => {
                warn!("Error: {:?}", e);
                buffer1 = [0u16; ADC_BUF_SIZE / 2];
                let _ = adc.start();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Would fail this assertion at runtime:
`assertion failed: n < 6usize`

After investigating the stm32 reference manual and the PAC, it turns out that n in the sequence was not reset whenever a new ADC regular sequence register was used. For example, _sqr2_ is indexed at 6, which would naturally be out of bounds for the register:
`Sequence::Seven => T::regs().sqr2().modify(|w| w.set_sq(6, channel.channel()))`

This n value is used to select which of the sequences in the register should be set, and should therefore indexed at 0 for every register:
```
#[doc = "7th conversion in regular sequence"]
#[inline(always)]
pub fn set_sq(&mut self, n: usize, val: u8) {
    assert!(n < 6usize);
    let offs = 0usize + n * 5usize;
    self.0 = (self.0 & !(0x1f << offs)) | (((val as u32) & 0x1f) << offs);
}
```
here is how the register is defined in the reference manual
![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7e7d9849-83c4-44b4-94a4-4d50a11cb2d6)

To fix this, at sequence 7 and 13 n is reset to 0 so that the register is indexed correctly

This adds support for doc comments in the `bind_interrupts` macro, allowing them to be better documented.

**Example usage:**

```rust
bind_interrupts!(
    /// Interrupt handlers
    struct Irqs {
        /// An interrupt handler for device x
        USART3 => BufferedInterruptHandler<USART3>;
        /// An interrupt handler for device y
        USART2 => BufferedInterruptHandler<USART2>;
    }
);
```

